ass’s Account of German Wartime Suffering in Beim Häuten der Zwiebel: Mind in Mourning or Boy Adventurer? -- t13: Jackboots and Jeans: The Private and the Political in Uwe Timm’s Am Beispiel meines Bruders -- t14: Memory-Work in Recent German Novels: What (if Any) Limits Remain on Empathy with the “German Experience” of the Second World War? -- t15: “Secondary Suffering” and Victimhood: The “Other” of German Identity in Bernhard Schlink’s “Die Beschneidung” and Maxim Biller’s “Harlem Holocaust” -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFirst comprehensive look at how today's German literary fiction deals with questions of German victimhood.In recent years it has become much more accepted in Germany to consider aspects of the Second World War in which Germans were not perpetrators, but victims: the Allied bombing campaign, expulsions of "ethnic" Germans, mass rapes of German women, and postwar internment and persecution. An explosion of literary fiction on these topics has accompanied this trend. Sebald's The Air War and Literature and Grass's Crabwalk are key texts, but there are many others; the great majority seek not to revise German responsibility for the Holocaust but to balance German victimhood and German perpetration. This book of essays is the first in English to examine closely the variety ofthese texts. An opening section on the 1950s -- a decade of intense literary engagement with German victimhood before the focus shifted to German perpetration -- provides context, drawing parallels but also noting differences between the immediate postwar period and today. The second section focuses on key texts written since the mid-1990s shifts in perspectives on the Nazi past, on perpetration and victimhood, on "ordinary Germans," and on the balance between historical empathy and condemnation. Contributors: Karina Berger, Elizabeth Boa, Stephen Brockmann, David Clarke, Mary Cosgrove, Rick Crownshaw, Helen Finch, Frank Finlay, Katharina Hall, Colette Lawson, Caroline Schaumann, Helmut Schmitz, Kathrin Schödel, and Stuart Taberner. Stuart Taberner is Professor of Contemporary German Literature, Culture, and Society at the University of Leeds. Karina Berger holds a PhD in German from the University of Leeds.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aAllied Bombing Campaign.  aAllied bombing campaign.  aBalance.  aContemporary Debates.  aExpulsions.  aGerman Literary Fiction.  aGerman Perpetration.  aGerman Responsibility.  aGerman Victimhood.  aGerman literary fiction.  aHolocaust.  aInternment.  aMass Rapes.  aPersecution.  aPostwar Germany.  aSecond World War.  aWorld War II.  aexpulsions.  ainternment.  amass rapes.  aperpetration.  apersecution.  avictims.1 aBerger, Karina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerger, Karina, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBoa, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrockmann, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCosgrove, Mary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrownshaw, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinch, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFinlay, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLawson, Colette, econtribu